{
  "doc_id": "3155",
  "text": "Many studies have found at least partial support for the 'evolution of increased competitive ability' (EICA) hypothesis which predicts that plants introduced into an environment that lacks their usual herbivores will experience selection favouring individuals that allocate less energy to defence and more to growth and reproduction (eg, [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] Jakobs et al., 2004; Maron et al., 2004; [CITATION_4] . Other studies found no support for EICA (eg, [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] or the opposite of what EICA predicts [CITATION_8] . However, only a few studies provided a full test of the EICA hypothesis by addressing both growth and defence in the same species [CITATION_9] . Elegant evidence for the EICA hypothesis was recently provided by [CITATION_10] . By examining herbarium specimens of alien Pastinaca sativa in North America over 152 years, they revealed phytochemical shifts towards increased toxicity coincident with the accidental introduction of a major herbivore from its native range. Overall, there is reasonable empirical evidence that genetic differentiation through rapid evolutionary change plays an important role in plant invasions [CITATION_11] . Nevertheless, available evidence suggests that some invaders are 'born' (released from fitness constraints), and some are 'made' (they evolve invasiveness after colonization) (sensu Ellstrand and Schierenbeck, 2000) , and that the relative importance of ecological and evolutionary forces seems to be unique to each plant invasion episode.",
